# Project: Timeless
# Role: Senior Android Developer & Software Architect
# Description: A minimalist, local-first time-awareness and micro-diary app. The goal is to encourage reflection and reduce doom-scrolling without causing anxiety.

## Core Philosophy & Constraints
- STRICTLY LOCAL-FIRST: No external backend servers, no Firebase, no cloud syncing. All data lives on the device.
- NO INTERNET PERMISSION: Do not add `<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.INTERNET" />` unless explicitly requested for a specific local API (e.g., reverse geocoding via local service).
- ZERO-BLOAT STORAGE: Do NOT copy image files into the app's internal storage. Always save the original file URI (path), file name, EXIF data, and generate a tiny Base64 micro-thumbnail (max 5KB).
- ANTI-ANXIETY UI: Do not use literal countdown numbers for time left. Use dots, shapes, or abstract representations in Jetpack Compose.
- BATTERY EFFICIENT: Background tasks (WorkManager) must only run within a 30-60 minute window before the user's scheduled reminder time.

## Tech Stack
- Language: Kotlin
- UI Toolkit: Jetpack Compose (Material 3)
- Local Database: Room Database (SQLite)
- Background Tasks: WorkManager
- Location/Sensors: Fused Location Provider API & SensorManager (for Gyroscope/Screen State)
- Architecture: MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel) with Clean Architecture principles (Data, Domain, Presentation layers).

## Coding Standards
- Use `build.gradle.kts` (Kotlin DSL) for all Gradle files.
- Ensure Gradle properties are optimized for Apple Silicon (ARM64) compilation.
- Use Coroutines and Flows for all asynchronous operations and database observing.
- Keep Room Entities flat and highly normalized.
- Separate UI State from UI Events in Compose ViewModels.